Opening Elevation: northwest 0.54 m below Sub datum 90 D or 905.390 m; northeast 0.50 m below Sub datum 90 D or 905.430 m; center 0.27 m below Sub datum 90 C or 905.339 m; southwest 1.00 m below Sub datum 90 A or 905.309 m; southeast 1.01 m below Sub datum 90 A or 905.299 m.

This massive soil locus began 3.06 m north of the cistern’s southwest channel opening, and continued throughout the Locus 3 channel all the way to the Locus 10 capstone at the trench’s north extent. For much of its extent, Locus 8 was rather unextraordinary in its content, although it did contain a large number of tesserae and a significant amount of painted plaster, probably representing washdown from homes on the hill behind the Great Temple. Among the finds were remnants of wood, a small crude ceramic figure, perhaps ceremonial, depicting the legs of a human on a small pedestal in low-relief, and three coins, all small bronze pieces and found in the last days of excavation, more to the north of the trench. A number of partial lamps, mostly of Nabataean types, were also discovered in this area. Although this fill seems to show a good deal of domestic wash, it should not be viewed merely as a sampling of this type due to its great depth and length, which suggest that its artifactual material came from any number of places and that the deposition of this fill took place over a long period of time following the destruction and disuse of the once capped west channel. The Munsell color of this soil was 10YR4/4 Dark Yellowish Brown.

Throughout nearly the full extent of the Locus 3 channel on the west side of the East Plaza.
XI

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Fill throughout Locus 3 channel
XII
Continued accumulation of debris in the canalization channels.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of large architectural features and the primary deposition of fluvial wash. Debris accumulates in the Shrine Room followed by major collapse. The West Walkway Wall collapses and the Residential Quarter is destroyed.

IX
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue. Upper levels of fluvial wash are deposited. Rooms A and B are abandoned.
Locus 12, channel plastering, Locus 16, bedrock, Locus 10, capstone, Locus 11, capstone mortar, and Locus 14, channel plaster fallout.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.

Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of 512. Fill accumulates following the disuse of the canalization systems. The remains of two bodies are found in the upper level fluvial deposits. Localized burning in some areas.
